	     <tr><td valign=top id=fs8 class=mform><span id=notbold>By:</span> <a href=poster.html?user=26810><span id= >Maldisdain</span></a><br><span id=notbold>9 posts<br><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent [3.40]</td><td valign=top class=mform width=100%><p>To be perfectly honest, I think it would be somewhat of a waste to give the Gauntlets of Dragon Slaying to a warrior.&nbsp;&nbsp;The benefits that the Gauntlets provide would be largely lost on the average warrior capable of butchering Yelinak (haste, non-melee related stats), and, though the 9 strength and resists are fabulous, it becomes fairly difficult for a Warlord to have a buffed strength of under 255.<br><br>Indeed, the 30 ac of these gauntlets is EQUAL to the ac on the Warlord's gauntlets, and the haste is likely comparable to the Cloak of the Flames or the oh-so-common Cloak of the Crystaline Waters.  <br><br>The 75 hps are far more significant to a ranger, paladin or shadowknight, and the haste and mana-int/wis are extremely helpful to these auxilary melee classes as well.<br><br>Would they be lovely for any class?  Of course.  In fact, they may well be worth giving to clerics, because of the fantastic resists they offer, coupled with extra hps, mana, and wisdom, which allow even *easier* equipment swapping, and make high-end AoE encounters significantly easier.  With the wonders of Specialize, 75 mana is half a complete heal, which, in the long run, is a hell of a lot better than only 75 more hps on your main tank.<br></p>&nbsp;<br><span class=sm>----------------------------</span><br>Sage Maldisdain Atheist<br>**** C o e r c e r ****<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;   of Cazic Thule<br></td></tr>
